---
import Layout from '../layouts/Layout.astro';
import ScrollReveal from '../components/ScrollReveal.astro';
import Accordion from '../components/Accordion.astro';
import RoadworksMap from '../components/RoadworksMap.astro';
---

<Layout
  title="Roads & Roadworks | Tom Pickup"
  description="Burnley's road network: current roadworks, TTROs, major projects, problem areas, and the £650M Lancashire highways backlog. Report potholes and track repairs."
>
  <!-- Hero -->
  <section class="rw-hero">
    <div class="container">
      <ScrollReveal>
        <div class="rw-hero-inner">
          <span class="badge badge-teal">Highways &amp; Transport</span>
          <h1>Roads &amp; Roadworks</h1>
          <p class="hero-sub">
            Current roadworks, active traffic orders, major projects, and everything you need
            to know about Burnley&rsquo;s road network. Lancashire County Council is the highways
            authority responsible for all roads except the M65 motorway.
          </p>
          <div class="hero-stats">
            <div class="hero-stat">
              <span class="hero-stat-value">&pound;650M+</span>
              <span class="hero-stat-label">Highways Backlog</span>
            </div>
            <div class="hero-stat">
              <span class="hero-stat-value">&pound;72M</span>
              <span class="hero-stat-label">2026/27 Investment</span>
            </div>
            <div class="hero-stat">
              <span class="hero-stat-value">7,400 km</span>
              <span class="hero-stat-label">LCC Road Network</span>
            </div>
            <div class="hero-stat">
              <span class="hero-stat-value">&pound;55M</span>
              <span class="hero-stat-label">Levelling Up Programme</span>
            </div>
          </div>
        </div>
      </ScrollReveal>
    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- Live Roadworks Map -->
  <section class="map-section">
    <div class="container">
      <ScrollReveal>
        <div class="section-header">
          <span class="badge badge-red">Live Data</span>
          <h2>Live Roadworks Map</h2>
          <p class="section-sub">
            All current and planned roadworks across Burnley Borough, updated every 2 hours
            from Lancashire County Council&rsquo;s official highways database. Click any marker for details.
          </p>
        </div>
      </ScrollReveal>
      <RoadworksMap />
    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- Who Maintains What -->
  <section class="responsibility-section">
    <div class="container">
      <ScrollReveal>
        <div class="section-header">
          <h2 class="section-heading">Who Maintains What?</h2>
          <p class="section-subtitle">Different organisations are responsible for different parts of the road network</p>
        </div>
        <div class="resp-grid stagger-children">
          <div class="resp-card">
            <span class="resp-badge" style="background: rgba(18, 182, 207, 0.12); color: #12b6cf;">County Council</span>
            <h3>Lancashire County Council</h3>
            <p>
              All A-roads, B-roads, and local roads. Potholes, resurfacing, street lighting,
              drainage, bridges, traffic signals, road markings, and winter gritting.
              Also responsible for the M65 from Junction 10 to Junction 14.
            </p>
            <a href="https://www.lancashire.gov.uk/roads-parking-and-travel/report-it/" class="resp-link" target="_blank" rel="noopener">
              Report to LCC
              <svg width="14" height="14" viewBox="0 0 24 24" fill="none" stroke="currentColor" stroke-width="2" stroke-linecap="round" stroke-linejoin="round"><path d="M18 13v6a2 2 0 0 1-2 2H5a2 2 0 0 1-2-2V8a2 2 0 0 1 2-2h6"></path><polyline points="15 3 21 3 21 9"></polyline><line x1="10" y1="14" x2="21" y2="3"></line></svg>
            </a>
          </div>
          <div class="resp-card">
            <span class="resp-badge" style="background: rgba(48, 209, 88, 0.12); color: #30d158;">National Highways</span>
            <h3>National Highways</h3>
            <p>
              The M65 motorway from the M6 (Junction 1) to Junction 10 at Burnley Barracks.
              Also manages the A56 south of Burnley toward Manchester.
              Different reporting process from LCC.
            </p>
            <a href="https://nationalhighways.co.uk/report-an-issue/" class="resp-link" target="_blank" rel="noopener">
              Report to National Highways
              <svg width="14" height="14" viewBox="0 0 24 24" fill="none" stroke="currentColor" stroke-width="2" stroke-linecap="round" stroke-linejoin="round"><path d="M18 13v6a2 2 0 0 1-2 2H5a2 2 0 0 1-2-2V8a2 2 0 0 1 2-2h6"></path><polyline points="15 3 21 3 21 9"></polyline><line x1="10" y1="14" x2="21" y2="3"></line></svg>
            </a>
          </div>
          <div class="resp-card">
            <span class="resp-badge" style="background: rgba(255, 159, 10, 0.12); color: #ff9f0a;">Utility Companies</span>
            <h3>Gas, Water, Electric, Broadband</h3>
            <p>
              Many roadworks are caused by utility companies (Cadent Gas, United Utilities,
              Electricity North West, Openreach) digging up roads. LCC coordinates but cannot
              always control the timing.
            </p>
          </div>
        </div>
      </ScrollReveal>
    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- Active TTROs -->
  <section class="ttro-section">
    <div class="container">
      <ScrollReveal>
        <div class="section-header">
          <h2 class="section-heading">Active Traffic Orders (TTROs)</h2>
          <p class="section-subtitle">
            Temporary Traffic Regulation Orders currently in force across Burnley borough.
            These are legal orders that allow road closures, diversions, and parking restrictions for roadworks.
          </p>
        </div>

        <div class="ttro-list stagger-children">
          <div class="ttro-card">
            <div class="ttro-header">
              <h3>Padiham Road</h3>
              <span class="ttro-status ttro-active">Active</span>
            </div>
            <p class="ttro-detail">Temporary traffic regulation between Burnley Barracks Interchange and Ightenhill Park Lane. Related to the &pound;55M Levelling Up highway improvement programme.</p>
            <span class="ttro-ref">Ref: TTRO-02</span>
          </div>

          <div class="ttro-card">
            <div class="ttro-header">
              <h3>Accrington Road, Burnley</h3>
              <span class="ttro-status ttro-amended">Amended</span>
            </div>
            <p class="ttro-detail">Date amendment to existing traffic regulation order. Accrington Road is a key route connecting Burnley to the M65 Junction 9 via the Rosegrove junction.</p>
            <span class="ttro-ref">Ref: TTRO-08 Amendment</span>
          </div>

          <div class="ttro-card">
            <div class="ttro-header">
              <h3>Barden Lane, Burnley</h3>
              <span class="ttro-status ttro-active">Active</span>
            </div>
            <p class="ttro-detail">Traffic regulation in force from 16 February to 23 March 2026. Near the Lower Manor Lane junction. One of the roads identified by Burnley MP as severely affected by roadworks.</p>
            <span class="ttro-ref">Ref: TTRO-02 + TTRO-08</span>
            <span class="ttro-dates">16 Feb 2026 to 23 Mar 2026</span>
          </div>

          <div class="ttro-card">
            <div class="ttro-header">
              <h3>Deer Park Road, Burnley</h3>
              <span class="ttro-status ttro-short">Short Notice</span>
            </div>
            <p class="ttro-detail">Single-day traffic regulation order.</p>
            <span class="ttro-ref">Ref: TTRO-02</span>
            <span class="ttro-dates">10 Mar 2026 to 11 Mar 2026</span>
          </div>

          <div class="ttro-card">
            <div class="ttro-header">
              <h3>Queen Victoria Road, Burnley</h3>
              <span class="ttro-status ttro-active">Active</span>
            </div>
            <p class="ttro-detail">Temporary traffic regulation order in effect.</p>
            <span class="ttro-ref">Ref: TTRO-02</span>
          </div>

          <div class="ttro-card">
            <div class="ttro-header">
              <h3>Moseley Road, Burnley</h3>
              <span class="ttro-status ttro-active">Active</span>
            </div>
            <p class="ttro-detail">Temporary traffic regulation order in effect.</p>
            <span class="ttro-ref">Ref: TTRO-02</span>
          </div>
        </div>

        <div class="ttro-source">
          <a href="https://www.lancashire.gov.uk/roads-parking-and-travel/roads/roadworks-and-traffic-regulation-orders/temporary/?District=Burnley" target="_blank" rel="noopener">
            <svg width="14" height="14" viewBox="0 0 24 24" fill="none" stroke="currentColor" stroke-width="2" stroke-linecap="round" stroke-linejoin="round"><path d="M18 13v6a2 2 0 0 1-2 2H5a2 2 0 0 1-2-2V8a2 2 0 0 1 2-2h6"></path><polyline points="15 3 21 3 21 9"></polyline><line x1="10" y1="14" x2="21" y2="3"></line></svg>
            View all Burnley TTROs on LCC website
          </a>
          <span class="ttro-updated">Last checked: 4 March 2026</span>
        </div>
      </ScrollReveal>
    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- Roadworks Coordination Issue -->
  <section class="chaos-section">
    <div class="container">
      <ScrollReveal>
        <div class="chaos-card">
          <div class="chaos-inner">
            <span class="chaos-label">February &ndash; March 2026</span>
            <h2>The Roadworks Coordination Problem</h2>
            <p>
              In early 2026, multiple major roadworks schemes hit Burnley simultaneously. The &pound;55M Levelling Up
              programme introduced a one-way system on Manchester Road. Colne Road had two-way signals for
              highway improvements. Hammerton Street was closed. Utility companies were digging on Accrington Road and Barden Lane.
            </p>
            <p>
              Burnley&rsquo;s MP described conditions as &ldquo;utterly unmanageable.&rdquo; Journeys normally
              taking 10 minutes were taking over an hour. Businesses reported lost footfall, inability to receive deliveries,
              and property damage from diverted HGV traffic.
            </p>
            <div class="chaos-roads">
              <span class="chaos-road">Manchester Road</span>
              <span class="chaos-road">Colne Road</span>
              <span class="chaos-road">Hammerton Street</span>
              <span class="chaos-road">Accrington Road</span>
              <span class="chaos-road">Barden Lane</span>
              <span class="chaos-road">Rossendale Road</span>
              <span class="chaos-road">Centenary Way</span>
            </div>
            <p class="chaos-note">
              The core issue: LCC controls the highways, but the Levelling Up programme is partly funded and managed
              by central government with Burnley Borough Council. Utility companies (Cadent Gas, United Utilities, Openreach)
              have statutory rights to dig up roads with limited council control over timing. Better coordination between
              all parties is essential.
            </p>
          </div>
        </div>
      </ScrollReveal>
    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- Major Current Projects -->
  <section class="projects-section">
    <div class="container">
      <ScrollReveal>
        <div class="section-header">
          <h2 class="section-heading">Major Projects (2025&ndash;2026)</h2>
          <p class="section-subtitle">
            Significant highway schemes currently underway or recently completed in the Burnley area
          </p>
        </div>

        <div class="project-cards stagger-children">
          <div class="project-card project-highlight">
            <div class="project-badge">&pound;55M</div>
            <h3>Levelling Up East Lancashire</h3>
            <p class="project-funder">Funded by: &pound;50M Government Levelling Up Fund + &pound;5M LCC</p>
            <p>
              The largest highways investment in East Lancashire in decades. Three connected projects
              transforming roads across Burnley, Nelson, and Rawtenstall.
            </p>
            <div class="project-details">
              <div class="project-sub">
                <h4>Manchester Road (Burnley Town Centre)</h4>
                <p>
                  One-way system introduced February 2026 between Nelson Square and Red Lion Street.
                  Wider pavements, upgraded pedestrian crossings, refreshed public spaces. Part of
                  the Civic Quarter Masterplan connecting Manchester Road Station to the bus station.
                  Has caused significant disruption and congestion during works.
                </p>
              </div>
              <div class="project-sub">
                <h4>Colne Road Improvements</h4>
                <p>
                  Major highway works from January 2026, potentially running to August 2026.
                  Two-way traffic signals during construction. Wider pavements, upgraded pedestrian
                  crossings, and new average speed cameras installed following stakeholder feedback.
                </p>
              </div>
              <div class="project-sub">
                <h4>Hammerton Street</h4>
                <p>
                  Highway improvement works from January to April 2026. Part of the wider
                  town centre connectivity improvements.
                </p>
              </div>
            </div>
          </div>

          <div class="project-card">
            <div class="project-badge">&pound;6.1M</div>
            <h3>Town2Turf Scheme</h3>
            <p class="project-funder">Funded by: Levelling Up Fund</p>
            <p>
              Improving links between Burnley town centre and Turf Moor stadium. The Centenary Way
              roundabout at Yorkshire Street and Church Street has been demolished and replaced with a
              signalised junction. Yorkshire Street aqueduct (the culvert carrying the Leeds and Liverpool
              Canal over the road) has been renovated. The old pedestrian subway has been decommissioned
              and landscaped. New crossings, paving, seating, and lighting installed.
            </p>
          </div>

          <div class="project-card">
            <div class="project-badge">&pound;72M</div>
            <h3>LCC 2026/27 Highways Programme</h3>
            <p class="project-funder">Funded by: &pound;48.5M DfT + &pound;18.5M LCC + carry-over</p>
            <p>
              Reform&rsquo;s first full highways capital programme. Focus on the roads residents
              use every day, not just strategic routes. Includes resurfacing, pothole repair,
              drainage, street lighting, and bridge maintenance across the county. Lancashire
              has committed &pound;45 million specifically for pothole and highway repairs over three years.
            </p>
          </div>
        </div>
      </ScrollReveal>
    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- Major Roads Guide -->
  <section class="roads-section">
    <div class="container">
      <ScrollReveal>
        <div class="section-header">
          <h2 class="section-heading">Burnley&rsquo;s Road Network</h2>
          <p class="section-subtitle">
            The major routes through and around Burnley, what they connect, and known issues
          </p>
        </div>

        <div class="roads-accordions">
          <Accordion title="M65 Motorway (Junctions 9, 10, 11)" defaultOpen={true}>
            <div class="road-detail">
              <div class="road-meta">
                <span class="road-tag">Motorway</span>
                <span class="road-maintainer">National Highways (J1-10) / LCC (J10-14)</span>
              </div>
              <p>
                The M65 runs east-west across Lancashire from the M6 near Preston through Blackburn,
                Accrington, and Burnley, ending at Colne. Burnley is served by three junctions:
              </p>
              <ul>
                <li><strong>Junction 9</strong> &mdash; Rosegrove. Access to Accrington Road, Rossendale Road, and south Burnley. Connects to the A679.</li>
                <li><strong>Junction 10</strong> &mdash; Burnley Barracks Interchange. The main junction for Burnley town centre via Cavalry Way. A large two-island roundabout spanning 500 metres. Known air quality exceedance area.</li>
                <li><strong>Junction 11</strong> &mdash; Barracks/Brierfield. Access to north Burnley and Brierfield via the A6114.</li>
              </ul>
              <div class="road-issue">
                <strong>Safety concerns:</strong> A series of fatal crashes in 2024 prompted calls for an urgent safety review
                of the M65 between Junctions 5 and 14. A multi-vehicle collision at Junction 9 in October 2024
                killed one person. Much of the M65 is unlit east of Blackburn. National Highways completed
                an &pound;84M safety programme in 2004 but concerns persist.
              </div>
            </div>
          </Accordion>

          <Accordion title="A56 (Burnley to Manchester)">
            <div class="road-detail">
              <div class="road-meta">
                <span class="road-tag">A-Road</span>
                <span class="road-maintainer">National Highways / LCC</span>
              </div>
              <p>
                Runs south from Burnley as a dual carriageway, skirting the western edge of the town.
                Links to the M66 motorway heading toward Manchester and the M62. This is the primary
                north-south route connecting Burnley to Greater Manchester and is heavily used by commuters.
              </p>
            </div>
          </Accordion>

          <Accordion title="A671 (Cavalry Way / through Padiham)">
            <div class="road-detail">
              <div class="road-meta">
                <span class="road-tag">A-Road</span>
                <span class="road-maintainer">LCC</span>
              </div>
              <p>
                Runs south from Bacup over Deerplay Moor into Burnley, crossing the A646 at the town
                centre. North of Burnley it becomes a primary road at M65 Junction 10 (Cavalry Way),
                then passes through Padiham as Main Street, bypasses Whalley, and ends at the A59.
              </p>
              <div class="road-issue">
                <strong>Air quality:</strong> A 271-metre section at Junction 10 exceeds annual NO2 limits.
                43% of nitrogen oxides come from cars. The large motorway junction with two traffic islands
                is a known bottleneck causing idling traffic.
              </div>
            </div>
          </Accordion>

          <Accordion title="A679 (Accrington Road / Burnley Road, Hapton)">
            <div class="road-detail">
              <div class="road-meta">
                <span class="road-tag">A-Road</span>
                <span class="road-maintainer">LCC</span>
              </div>
              <p>
                Connects Burnley westward to Accrington via Hapton. Speed enforcement operates on the
                30mph section at Hapton. The junction with Rossendale Road and Liverpool Road near
                M65 Junction 9 (Rosegrove junction) is a known congestion hotspot, widened in a
                12-month project in 2019-2020 but still regularly disrupted by utility works and
                housing development traffic.
              </p>
            </div>
          </Accordion>

          <Accordion title="A646 (Todmorden Road / Rossendale Road)">
            <div class="road-detail">
              <div class="road-meta">
                <span class="road-tag">A-Road</span>
                <span class="road-maintainer">LCC</span>
              </div>
              <p>
                Runs south-east from Burnley town centre toward Todmorden and West Yorkshire through
                the Cliviger Gorge. A key cross-Pennine route carrying significant HGV traffic.
                The road follows the River Calder valley and is prone to flooding in heavy rainfall.
              </p>
            </div>
          </Accordion>

          <Accordion title="A682 (Centenary Way / to Rawtenstall and Nelson)">
            <div class="road-detail">
              <div class="road-meta">
                <span class="road-tag">A-Road</span>
                <span class="road-maintainer">LCC</span>
              </div>
              <p>
                Runs south to Rawtenstall through Rossendale and north-east to Nelson and the
                Yorkshire Dales. This road is carried through Burnley town centre on the
                <strong>Centenary Way Viaduct</strong>, a seven-span continuous bridge that underwent
                a &pound;1.65M refurbishment in 2015-16, addressing chloride-induced concrete damage
                from decades of de-icing salt, bearing replacement, expansion joints, and deck waterproofing.
              </p>
            </div>
          </Accordion>

          <Accordion title="Key Local Roads">
            <div class="road-detail">
              <div class="local-roads-grid">
                <div class="local-road">
                  <h4>Padiham Road</h4>
                  <p>One of Burnley&rsquo;s oldest routes connecting to Padiham, Whalley, and Blackburn. Currently subject to a TTRO for improvement works.</p>
                </div>
                <div class="local-road">
                  <h4>Manchester Road</h4>
                  <p>Key gateway into Burnley from the south. Currently under one-way system for the &pound;55M Levelling Up programme. Severe congestion reported.</p>
                </div>
                <div class="local-road">
                  <h4>Colne Road</h4>
                  <p>Major improvements underway (Jan&ndash;Aug 2026). Two-way signals during construction. New average speed cameras installed.</p>
                </div>
                <div class="local-road">
                  <h4>Briercliffe Road</h4>
                  <p>Connects Burnley northeast to Briercliffe village. Subject to emergency traffic regulation orders for maintenance.</p>
                </div>
                <div class="local-road">
                  <h4>Barden Lane</h4>
                  <p>Local road identified as severely affected by concurrent roadworks. Active TTRO near Lower Manor Lane junction.</p>
                </div>
                <div class="local-road">
                  <h4>Brunshaw Road / Brunshaw Avenue</h4>
                  <p>Listed for resurfacing work from Brunshaw Road to Redlees Road, plus surface dressing.</p>
                </div>
              </div>
            </div>
          </Accordion>
        </div>
      </ScrollReveal>
    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- Problem Areas -->
  <section class="problems-section">
    <div class="container">
      <ScrollReveal>
        <div class="section-header">
          <h2 class="section-heading">Known Problem Areas</h2>
          <p class="section-subtitle">
            Locations with recurring congestion, safety concerns, or infrastructure issues
          </p>
        </div>

        <div class="problems-grid stagger-children">
          <div class="problem-card">
            <span class="problem-icon" style="color: #ff453a;">
              <svg width="24" height="24" viewBox="0 0 24 24" fill="none" stroke="currentColor" stroke-width="2" stroke-linecap="round" stroke-linejoin="round"><path d="M10.29 3.86L1.82 18a2 2 0 0 0 1.71 3h16.94a2 2 0 0 0 1.71-3L13.71 3.86a2 2 0 0 0-3.42 0z"></path><line x1="12" y1="9" x2="12" y2="13"></line><line x1="12" y1="17" x2="12.01" y2="17"></line></svg>
            </span>
            <h3>Rosegrove Junction (M65 J9)</h3>
            <p>
              Accrington Road, Rossendale Road, and Liverpool Road junction. Widened 2019-20 but
              still a bottleneck from housing development traffic and repeated utility works.
              Gas main installation caused months of disruption.
            </p>
          </div>

          <div class="problem-card">
            <span class="problem-icon" style="color: #ff9f0a;">
              <svg width="24" height="24" viewBox="0 0 24 24" fill="none" stroke="currentColor" stroke-width="2" stroke-linecap="round" stroke-linejoin="round"><path d="M10.29 3.86L1.82 18a2 2 0 0 0 1.71 3h16.94a2 2 0 0 0 1.71-3L13.71 3.86a2 2 0 0 0-3.42 0z"></path><line x1="12" y1="9" x2="12" y2="13"></line><line x1="12" y1="17" x2="12.01" y2="17"></line></svg>
            </span>
            <h3>Cavalry Way / Gannow Roundabout</h3>
            <p>
              M65 Junction 10 (Burnley Barracks Interchange). One of Burnley&rsquo;s busiest
              junctions. Two-island roundabout spanning 500 metres. Frequent accidents and
              congestion. Air quality exceedance area for NO2.
            </p>
          </div>

          <div class="problem-card">
            <span class="problem-icon" style="color: #ff453a;">
              <svg width="24" height="24" viewBox="0 0 24 24" fill="none" stroke="currentColor" stroke-width="2" stroke-linecap="round" stroke-linejoin="round"><path d="M10.29 3.86L1.82 18a2 2 0 0 0 1.71 3h16.94a2 2 0 0 0 1.71-3L13.71 3.86a2 2 0 0 0-3.42 0z"></path><line x1="12" y1="9" x2="12" y2="13"></line><line x1="12" y1="17" x2="12.01" y2="17"></line></svg>
            </span>
            <h3>Manchester Road Corridor</h3>
            <p>
              The &pound;55M Levelling Up one-way system has caused severe disruption since February
              2026. Journeys normally taking 10 minutes reportedly taking over an hour.
              Businesses have reported lost footfall and delivery access problems.
            </p>
          </div>

          <div class="problem-card">
            <span class="problem-icon" style="color: #12b6cf;">
              <svg width="24" height="24" viewBox="0 0 24 24" fill="none" stroke="currentColor" stroke-width="2" stroke-linecap="round" stroke-linejoin="round"><path d="M21 10c0 7-9 13-9 13s-9-6-9-13a9 9 0 0 1 18 0z"></path><circle cx="12" cy="10" r="3"></circle></svg>
            </span>
            <h3>River Calder Flood Risk</h3>
            <p>
              The River Calder runs through Burnley town centre. Roads at risk include Centenary Way,
              Parker Lane, Hammerton Street, St. James Street, Curzon Street, and Calder Vale Road.
              The M65 eastbound between Junctions 11-12 flooded in October 2023.
            </p>
          </div>
        </div>
      </ScrollReveal>
    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- Bridge Infrastructure -->
  <section class="bridges-section">
    <div class="container">
      <ScrollReveal>
        <div class="section-header">
          <h2 class="section-heading">Bridge &amp; Structure Infrastructure</h2>
          <p class="section-subtitle">
            Key bridges and structures that are critical to Burnley&rsquo;s road network
          </p>
        </div>

        <div class="bridges-grid stagger-children">
          <div class="bridge-card">
            <h3>Centenary Way Viaduct</h3>
            <span class="bridge-carries">Carries: A682 through town centre</span>
            <p>
              Seven-span continuous bridge. &pound;1.65M refurbishment completed January 2016 after chloride
              damage from de-icing salt caused concrete spalling and exposed steel reinforcement.
              Bearings replaced, expansion joints replaced, deck waterproofed and resurfaced.
            </p>
          </div>
          <div class="bridge-card">
            <h3>Yorkshire Street Aqueduct</h3>
            <span class="bridge-carries">Carries: Leeds and Liverpool Canal over Yorkshire Street</span>
            <p>
              Renovated as part of the Town2Turf scheme. Yorkshire Street was closed for essential
              maintenance, with pavement widening under and around the aqueduct.
            </p>
          </div>
          <div class="bridge-card">
            <h3>East Lancashire Railway Bridges</h3>
            <span class="bridge-carries">Carries: Colne-Blackburn railway line</span>
            <p>
              Network Rail invested &pound;3.95M upgrading two railway bridges over the Leeds and
              Liverpool Canal on the East Lancashire line through Burnley.
            </p>
          </div>
          <div class="bridge-card">
            <h3>Rose Grove Viaduct</h3>
            <span class="bridge-carries">Carries: Copy Pit railway line (Todmorden-Burnley)</span>
            <p>
              Historic 100-foot-high railway viaduct on the line through the Cliviger Gorge.
              A landmark structure in the Burnley skyline.
            </p>
          </div>
        </div>
      </ScrollReveal>
    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- How to Get a Pothole Fixed -->
  <section class="pothole-section">
    <div class="container">
      <ScrollReveal>
        <div class="section-header">
          <h2 class="section-heading">How to Get a Pothole Fixed</h2>
          <p class="section-subtitle">
            The process, the timescales, and what to do if nothing happens
          </p>
        </div>

        <div class="pothole-steps stagger-children">
          <div class="pothole-step">
            <span class="step-number">1</span>
            <div class="step-content">
              <h3>Report It</h3>
              <p>
                Report the pothole on the
                <a href="https://www.lancashire.gov.uk/roads-parking-and-travel/report-it/" target="_blank" rel="noopener">LCC website</a>
                or call 0300 123 6780. Include the exact location, size, and a photo if possible.
                You&rsquo;ll get a reference number.
              </p>
            </div>
          </div>
          <div class="pothole-step">
            <span class="step-number">2</span>
            <div class="step-content">
              <h3>It Gets Assessed</h3>
              <p>
                LCC uses a risk-based assessment. Potholes deeper than 40mm on a carriageway are classed as
                &ldquo;safety defects&rdquo; and should be repaired within 20 working days (Cat 2) or 2 hours
                if they pose an immediate danger (Cat 1). Smaller defects go on the planned maintenance programme.
              </p>
            </div>
          </div>
          <div class="pothole-step">
            <span class="step-number">3</span>
            <div class="step-content">
              <h3>The Repair</h3>
              <p>
                Reform&rsquo;s approach has shifted to larger, more permanent repairs: averaging 6m&sup2; per repair
                (up from 2m&sup2;) at under &pound;100/m&sup2; (down from &pound;200/m&sup2;). The goal is
                fewer repeat visits to the same location.
              </p>
            </div>
          </div>
          <div class="pothole-step">
            <span class="step-number">4</span>
            <div class="step-content">
              <h3>If Nothing Happens</h3>
              <p>
                If the repair isn&rsquo;t done within the target timescale, you have three options:
                chase it via your LCC reference number, report it again on FixMyStreet (which creates
                a public record), or <a href="/contact/">contact me directly</a> and I will chase the
                highways department on your behalf.
              </p>
            </div>
          </div>
        </div>

        <div class="pothole-data-note">
          <strong>Data problem:</strong> LCC&rsquo;s HAMS asset management system is being decommissioned,
          which means the council currently cannot verify whether it is meeting its own pothole repair targets.
          This is being addressed but it means published repair statistics should be treated with caution.
        </div>
      </ScrollReveal>
    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- Speed Cameras & Safety -->
